Diabetes UK has active support groups working locally all over the United
Groups typically meet once a month, but they often also take part in many
other activities such as fundraising, campaigning and raising awareness.
Adjusting to the knowledge that you or a family member has diabetes takes time
and it is often helpful to meet other people who have been through a similar
situation. They can offer understanding, help and support at an important
A good way of finding this help is to join a local support group – a Diabetes
UK group. These groups offer people living with diabetes a chance to meet and
share experiences with others. They are all run by volunteers and typically
meet on a monthly basis, often with a speaker on a topic like diet or
> "Talking to people through the group has helped. I'm the sort of person who
> wants to help other people and I feel very strongly that the more knowledge
> people have, the better they can cope."
> Shona Freeborn, carer for her husband who has Type 1 diabetes and runs a
As well providing support and information, Diabetes UK groups also get
There are also some specialist groups – for parents, children and young people
Please note that Diabetes UK groups cannot give medical advice. They can only
talk about diabetes from their own experiences. If you need medical advice
please contact your local diabetes specialist nurse, or local diabetes centre.
No group in your area? Why not set up your own?
